==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ethylene
<hw>Eth"yl*ene</hw> <pr>(⟦ecr⟧th"⟦icr⟧l*⟦emac⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[From <er>Ethyl</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A colorless,
gaseous hydrocarbon, <chform>C2H4</chform>, forming an important
ingredient of illuminating gas, and also obtained by the action of
concentrated sulphuric acid in alcohol. It is an unsaturated compound
and combines directly with chlorine and bromine to form oily liquids
(Dutch liquid), -- hence called <altname>olefiant gas</altname>. Called
also <altname>ethene</altname>, <altname>elayl</altname>, and formerly,
<altname>bicarbureted hydrogen</altname>.</def> <-- is effective in
hastening the ripening of certain fruits. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Ethylene series</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>the
series of unsaturated hydrocarbons of which ethylene is the type, and
represented by the general formula <chform>CnH2n</chform>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ethylic</ent>⟦br⟧
